 <section id="process" class="mb-16">
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-4">7. Semi-Solid-State Manufacturing Process</h2>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">Understanding the manufacturing process helps you evaluate suppliers and set realistic timelines. Semi-solid-state battery production differs from conventional Li-polymer in several key areas:</p>
 <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
 <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-slate-200">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue text-sm mb-2"><span class="text-brandOrange font-black mr-2">01</span>Gel Electrolyte Mixing</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Unlike liquid electrolyte injection used in standard Li-polymer cells, semi-solid-state batteries use a specialized gel polymer mixing process. This requires dedicated equipment and dry-room conditions with less than 1% humidity.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-slate-200">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue text-sm mb-2"><span class="text-brandOrange font-black mr-2">02</span>Cell Assembly &amp; Formation</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">The electrode coating and stacking process is similar to Li-polymer, but the formation cycling takes 20-30% longer due to the gel electrolyte needing more time to fully penetrate the electrode materials.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-slate-200">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue text-sm mb-2"><span class="text-brandOrange font-black mr-2">03</span>Quality Control Testing</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Each cell undergoes rigorous testing including internal resistance measurement, capacity grading, and nail penetration tests to verify safety. Semi-solid-state cells must pass the same UN38.3 certification as conventional Li-polymer cells.</p>
 </div>
 </div>

 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-6">As production volumes increase and manufacturing processes mature, the cost gap between semi-solid-state and conventional Li-polymer cells is expected to narrow significantly. Several major Chinese battery manufacturers have announced capacity expansions for semi-solid-state production, signaling strong industry confidence in this technology's future. Brands that adopt semi-solid-state now will benefit from first-mover advantage in the safer battery market segment.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">According to <a href="https://www.marketsandmarkets.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange underline">MarketsAndMarkets</a>, the global power bank market is expected to reach $18.5 billion by 2028, growing at a CAGR of 8.2%. Semi-solid-state technology is expected to capture an increasing share of this growth as production scales and costs decline toward parity with conventional Li-polymer cells over the next 18-24 months.</p>

 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3 mt-8">OEM Development Timeline</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Developing a semi-solid-state power bank follows a structured process: cell specification and supplier qualification (2-3 weeks), BMS design optimized for gel electrolyte characteristics (2-3 weeks), PCBA and enclosure design (3-4 weeks), prototype assembly and testing including cycle life verification (3-4 weeks), certification (2-3 weeks for UN38.3), and mass production (3-4 weeks).</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Total timeline from concept to production-ready samples is approximately 12-17 weeks for a new OEM design. ODM solutions using existing semi-solid-state platforms can be ready in 5-7 weeks, making them ideal for brands entering the market quickly.</p>
 </div>
 </section>

